<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
Update 12/30/19
Today I went in for my regular haircut and had a very unique experience. Within 10 minutes of sitting down the power for the entire shopping center went down. Though the power went out, the staff working, made the best of the situation and made every attempt to finish my haircut. Though the power was out all 3 of the employees working worked together to hold camera lights to give light to the stylist cutting my hair (I was the only customer in the building at the time) which made me extremely happy with the amazing commitment and level of customer service given, going above and beyond what I could have hoped for in this situation. They apologized for the inconvenience, and made every attempt to do their best, which is all I could ask for. This particular establishment has always gone above and beyond in satisfying customer needs. I was more than satisfied with my haircut and even with minimal tools available, they did an amazing job which demonstrated to me the quality and level of expertise that goes into training Sports Clips employees. I wrote my previous review a year ago and the service has maintained it's amazing quality. If I could give 6 stars as a review I would, and I continue to look forward to coming back this location for many more years, Thank you for your amazing level of customer service Sports Clips Team!

This was my first time ever trying out a different haircut venue and it was probably the best experience I've ever had getting a haircut. Stephanie who cut my hair was very friendly and helped with the tiny details with my cut spending a gracious amount time cutting it, this made me feel really valued as a customer knowing the effort, quality, and time she spent. I will be returning to this sports clips for all my future haircuts!</Text>

Took my 2001 E46 330i in for recall airbag service and received a loaner from BMW Advisor ‚ÄúKenny Lew‚Äù. After receiving the loaner, my advisor told me the vehicle would be ready by the end of the day on Friday and that additional charges for the vehicle would accrue if the loaner was not dropped off by the allotted time. I received text updates when my vehicle was ready, however I had to let my advisor know that because I get off work at 5:30pm, I may not be able to drop off by 6pm (closing time).

I received passive aggressive texts from Kenny: ‚ÄúI was hoping to avoid this issue by informing you this morning the loaner had to be returned by 6pm today as the recall repair would be ready the same day‚Äù. I responded by saying I was sorry and that I didn‚Äôt know the service center would be closed all weekend.

The loaner service agreement says loaner vehicles should be dropped off no more than 12 hours after the vehicle is finished. It also states the check in time for the vehicle was on Monday at 7:23AM (checked out Friday at 7:23 AM). The loaner contract is confusing but still, I understood and signed the agreement.

When I came to pick up my vehicle on Monday and drop off the loaner vehicle, the nice lady at the desk took my loaner paperwork and checked the vehicle mileage and condition. When she came back she told me that I owed $89/day for a total of $178 for having the vehicle over the weekend. I expressed to her the issue I was having and could not make it back to the service center on time the previous Friday. She was accommodating and said she could knock down the price to $100. She also told me that Kenny had previously told her that I was told to deliver the vehicle on time, and that there should not be exceptions made for my case.

It truly seemed because I was a ‚Äúrecall customer,‚Äù I had a low judgement by my service advisor. I essentially had to talk to the manager to get the entire loaner fee waived. He was extremely professional, understanding, and accommodating of the situation. < Review>
I took my car to the Service facility like I have since I bought the car.
The check engine light was on and I could not get the car smoged.
I was told there were 4 items that would need to be fixed. The first three would cost around $1,500 but the third would probably cost $8,000 in labor alone.  The Car has 138,000 miles on it and I could not justify spending that kind of money repairing it when I could buy a used one for less than the repairs. The service person than asked if i would like to trade it in. I said no I already lease a brand new Jeep Grand Cherokee. I was bummed because I had taken care of the care impeccably and I had just put new tires on it. I did not want to give it to 1-877-cars for kids yet.  I then got lucky and a buddy told me about a guy in San Bruno with a business called The Shop and I reluctantly went there.  He said that the air flow problem they were talking about could be taken care of with some simple spray which cleared out the carbon buildup in the airflow unit.  He took three days and called me to come pick up my car and charged me $1,450 for everything. I got my car smoged and I am the happy owner of my old car. Should have been going to this guy all along.</Review>

< text>
Peter Pan BMW's service department has now on three occasions exceeded any expectations I'd normally have when it comes to service. They speak openly, friendly and treat me like someone who's actually valued. Their main Receptionist (blonde hair, sorry I don't remember her name) is one of the nicest people you could ever meet, she has excellent customer service skills and has a rare, genuine kindness that is hard to find nowadays. Nobody likes having to carve out time in their day to get their car serviced and I bet she has to deal with quite a few cranky, unhappy customers, but she comes across as someone who really likes what she does and she tries to make everyone's experience a bit better. Little things, like when asking how your day is, she's making eye contact and you can definitely tell she's being real, not just repeating the usual lines. I'm greeted the moment my feet cross thru the doorway.

I've had the Assistant Service Manager, Steve, personally help me each time I've brought my car in, and the guy couldn't be any better. He's a car enthusiast and also treated me like my concerns mattered more to him than "business as usual". I like him a lot.

I've only had two minor issues with my car separate from one regularly scheduled maintenance service done there, but they're the only place I ever want to deal with. Good people!</text>

Roel Vela and his team took good care of me and my BMW.
Setting up an appt. over the phone was easy. I was able to drop my BMW the next day and got a shuttle to the nearest Starbucks. Got a call from Roel about a software download issue which would cause them to keep the car overnight and urging me to pickup a loaner, which I did. The loaner was an excellent car, almost made me want to buy that next. Next am, got a voicemail from Roel telling me my car was ready for pickup. I drove in the loaner, and under 15 minutes, drove away with my BMW, which hasn't complained about anything yet. In all, I had a great experience, and would recommend Peter Pan BMW to anyone.<//Text>

<UserId.>104367362909119392250< /UserId.>< user_name>
theERP89</user_name>
<Date>1504756437567< /Date><rating>3<//rating>< review>
I'll be honest, the only reason I'm giving them 3 stars is for the shop itself, the atmosphere, a nice vintage vibe with a lot of cool pictures, antiques, and airplanes made of soda cans... All that's fine and dandy but the cuts themselves are mediocre. At least from the heavyset gentleman with the long black hair, his name escapes me at the moment, then again I don't think I ever even got his name as he doesn't speak. Not to me anyways.... He has messed my hair up more than once, facial hair as well.

Still, this is a go-to shop if your on a budget and need a quick cut. The wait is not long at all, in fact pretty fast service, and cheap. You get what you pay for.<//review>

< Review>
Great place with a lot of history. A real old school kind of place.This is the kind of place all men should get their hair cut.

Skillfull and no BS. No pushing to buy anything and I can gaurantee this is the coolest place you've ever had a fade.

Cash Only but there is a store across the street with an ATM. This place has my business from now on.</Review>

< review>
Small bookstore at the university. Not much there but the basics. Books, supplies, school memorabilia, there is a limited supply of computers. They only carry apple products on-site. No Microsoft or Google products although you can order other products through the book store website. There is a Target store, an office supply store, a hardware store nearby if toy can't find what you need. It's definitely the basics.</review>

{'time': 1550798518276, 'text': "Through my 25+ years in private practice, I have seen that a child's reaction to the dental environment, when accompanied by that parent, can be entirely different with one parent versus another.  This is quite common and normal.  It is not personal, but a child can react more favorably with the parent that most commonly brings them to the dentist.\nAs an office, when patients come in from a blended family, we do our best to develop a trusting relationship with both parents.  For you as a parent, I am always available anytime by phone for any\nquestions you may have.  Your child's experience is always number one."}< /resp>
< review>
I had a very negative experience with Dr. Porter. I know he is highly rated, I am sure he is an excellent dentist.

My situation is unusual and difficult to navigate. I share custody of my son, and the relationship between his father and I has just always been so difficult. I didn‚Äôt meet Dr. Porter until after he‚Äôd developed a strong relationship with my child‚Äôs dad, and I don‚Äôt know what was said about me, and I cannot blame Dr. Porter completely, but his manner and tone to me was so intimidating and unfriendly that I actually developed anxiety, and my son did as well.

In fact, my child started sobbing and would not sit in the chair. I had his baby brother with me as well, and I‚Äôd had no idea my son was going to be so anxious and upset he would not be able to cooperate with Dr. Porter, but Icould not devote myself completely to comforting and soothing him because I had my younger son with me as well, and Dr. Porter really just made me feel awful, in a situation that is inherently awful for everyone already.

I take my son to doctor‚Äôs appointments all the time, and I have never ever seen him be complete inconsolable, even when he got vaccinations.

According to Dr. Porter, he did not have this problem when he was with his dad, so I respect that. Maybe my son senses that his dad is comfortable with Dr. Porter, and that helped him feel comfortable. Indeed, my son‚Äôs dad seems to love Dr. Porter.

Either way, I love my son more than anything, and these kinds of situations are inherently painful, and it hurts even more when others who must deal with both of us seem not to remain neutral, which is what I feel happened here.

I am sure he is a fantastic clinician, and I think he did very well with my son‚Äôs teeth.  I wouldn‚Äôt discourage anyone from visiting Dr. Porter, but in my case, I believe my son will feel more secure with a practitioner who seems to have a professional level of compassion for the caregiver who is responsible for a given appointment. I think at least neutrality would be indicated here.

For this reason, when next I am taking my son to the dentist, I will exercise my right to take him to a dentist with whom I can build a rapport that will not be affected by the challenges inherent in having to align so many different motivations and personalities.<//review>

I contacted Shaw's after hours and they immediately came out to figure out what the problem was.  It turns out that our AC was not blowing sufficient cool air to take bring down our AC from 85 degrees.   While we were trying to decide what action to take, one night I woke up during the night because I smelled something burning.  My husband went outside to make sure that our AC was not on fire.  Turns out that our AC had finally gave out.  Our house was at 89 degrees inside and Shaw's came out and brought us a portable unit to use for free.  Luckily we had a service contract, so we only had to pay the regular service charge (no OT). Shaw's gave us an estimate, which included a new AC unit, new Duct work (orig duct work 1976), larger Air Vents (that allow more air to flow), Return Air Filter (sucks up the hot air and allows the circulation of cool air to flow) and the installation of a new Thermostat, Carbon Monoxide sensor/alarm, and Fire Alarms in all 3 bedrooms.  We also received 10 year Warranty on parts and labor, 2 year service plan.  They disposed of the old unit and all of the old ductwork, including the old unit. After an 1 1/2 hrs it was at 75 degrees.  We are so happy with the choice that we made to go with Shaw's.  I recommend them to anyone who is in need of AC or Heating services. <Review>I did a little research on the web looking for a HVAC service company with good reviews.  I chose Shaw's mainly because of the professional website and positive reviews.

I'm always a little apprehensive about hiring contractor's so I emailed Shaw's.  I got a call and we agreed upon a diagnostic at a convenient time for me.

Their tech, Brian, called and showed up early.  He greeted us, put on his shoe covers, and looked at my thermostat.  He told me what he was going to do and quickly got to work.  He saw me outside while he was working and gave me a little info on what he was doing and his suspicion on what might be wrong.  He also gave me a tip on using the built-in AC filter as an option to the in-house duct filter. As we spoke, he gave me the option of signing up for their maintenance program, but he didn't push it.  He suggested how it could save money even on today's visit.

Shortly thereafter, he came down to test the AC unit via the thermostat and went up to do some additional work.  By this time I opted for the maintenance agreement and he took care of maintenance right after the repair.

We then looked over the charges, discussed my questions, and Brain took off.

I was pleased at the efficiency and straight-forward and friendly interaction.

< Name>
Chase Slagle</Name>
<time>1618199392047<//time>< rate>
4< /rate>
< Review>
Our room was a dual queen bed (One for us and one for the kids) in the Silliman building, second floor. The room was comfortable enough and was well fitted for the getaway we were on. Cable TV and Wifi were provided, though don't expect to be able to stream movies at night with 1.5mbps download speeds.

The lodge is located only a couple miles from the Sherman Tree and Beetle rock, as well as the Sequoia Museum. The road from the southwest gate to the lodge is a fantastic journey of hairpin turns, incredible views from a height, and breathtaking cliffs without a guardrail for an hour. Fill up your tank before making the drive up!

The food is OK but nothing to write home about at the lodge, in fact, I would recommend to bring some snacks as everything is pricey. Which is to be somewhat expected being in the middle of the park.

The Arts & Crafts/Mission style of the lodge and cabins were very pleasing. Overall I had a very pleasant experience!</Review>

Lodge style hotel in a beautiful forest setting.  Yes the nightly rate is a bit high for the room/amenities you get but it's all about the location. Check in is in different location then rooms. Yes parking is away from rooms but it's not that far. The room was spacious, clean and the bed was comfortable. They welcome dogs too. Our room didn't have AC, even though it gets cool outside at night it's still warm inside. Ceiling fan helped. Very quiet at night. Free coffee in lobby in AM.< /review>

< Text>
First time to Sequoia Nat'l Park and it's beyond beautiful up here. Wuksachi Lodge is right at the center of all the main attractions and trails so definitely 5 stars for location. There is a lot of signage so it was easy to find. Because the Lodge is in the middle of the forest you see a ton of wildlife without even trying which is fantastic. The only down side is that it's the only place with a restaurant in all of Sequoia Nat'l Forest I believe so you have to eat at the Waksuchi Lodge restaurant. The food is pricey but really good. I was pleasantly surprised at the options, portion size and quality of the meals. There's a mini fridge in the room so definitely bring your own drinks and snacks. You can find other food options at the town at the base of the mountain called Three Rivers but it's about an hour drive from Waksuchi through winding mountain roads so a pain to go just for lunch or dinner.  The staff is super friendly and welcoming and really love the diversity of guests staying here. We stayed in a two queen room and it's very spacious with a small table with 3 chairs, closet, bench by the door to take dirty boots/clothes off, and average size bathroom.<//Text>

< Review>
Terrific stay at the Wuksachi. Everyone working there was wearing masks, plastic guards in place etc. Felt very safe considering the pandemic. John and Haley at the front desk were really wonderful, great sense of humor and very accommodating. We had book three separate room types across a few different platforms and were supposed to move every night. John and Haley worked hard to "merge" our reservations, ensuring we could stay in the same room for our entire stay. Food at the lodge was actually the best in the park IMO. Would 100% recommend staying here if you are visiting Sequoia Kings Canyon. It is also located very close to popular sights (Moro Rock, Crescent Meadow, General Sherman) and rooms are updated and comfortable.<//Review>

< user_id>
117832408789555351833</user_id>
<review>We recently spent two nights at the Wuksachi Lodge in Sequoia National Park. This is the feature park lodge excellently located just a few miles from major sightseeing in the Giant Forest section of the park.

Reservation was made 6 months in advance directly through the park website. Email confirmation was received immediately. 4pm Check-in at the main lodge was very slow, around 30 minutes due to two sets of guest ahead of us in the queue. Hopefully they will learn to check in guests quicker in the future.

Lobby area is nice, includes seating near a stone fireplace. There is a gift shop on site as well as a restaurant called the Peak. We had dinner here one night, it was quite poor (see separate review) so we opted to not eat here the next day.

Rooms are found in 3 separate buildings around 400 metres from the lodge. There is a carpark below. You have take your luggage rather far to get into the building and then up to your rooms. Rooms were decent but not what you'd expect for the room rates normally.

Space was good, furnishing a bit dated and decor common. Bed comfort just ok. Room came with sitting sofa and chair, desk with chair, fridge, flat screen TV and enough closet space for most. Bathroom space was fine, shower water pressure a bit weak but plenty of warm water. We paid higher rate for a room with a view. Our room was a first floor room overlooking the carpark. That felt like a wasted spend.

Overall, you are paying for the location with Wuksachi Lodge. We very much appreciated being so close to the Giant Forest, allowing us to visit early in the morning before too many tourists overwhelmed the trails and sights. It was nice being able to return to the lodge for a bit of a rest before heading back out midday. Otherwise, we felt rather meh about the room considering the high rates and would probably opt to stay elsewhere and just drive in for sightseeing next time.< /review></record></dataset><record>
<gmapID>0x80955e7bbfa947a1:0x569f3289d86ec019< /gmapID><review>We were delighted with our accommodations at the Lodge and they certainly surpassed our expectations. So much so we could very readily have stayed longer than the one night we were booked in for.
The food was okay but nothing out of the ordinary. Service was largely perfunctory rather than accomplished but I imagine recruitment must be quite a challenge given the location. We visited in September and got the feeling that many staff are simply getting a bit people-weary.
The location is beautiful and we loved the drive both up and down the mountain.<//review>< user_id>

< Review>
Even accounting for COVID-19 this establishment grossly over sells itself.
The rooms have not been updated in many years, carpets are not clean anywhere, and there were knobs missing from the dresser the TV sits on.
A/C consisted of a fan wedged into a window, there is no A/C that we found in our room.
Food choices are limited (COVID), however $17 for a frozen pizza is a stretch, especially when they are burned beyond recognition.  Check the boxes too because not only is there a good chance it's charred, it may not even be pizza.  Don't bother with the Bison burger either, any flavor it was supposed to have is cooked out of it.
We should have just camped.</Review>

< text>
Great place to go up and see snow during the winter months. Tons of hiking trails close to the lodge and several of the largest trees in the world. Make sure to bring chains if there is a chance of snow and take your time going up and down the roads as they can ice up. Highly recommend staying a few nights and bringing up some food to snack on by the outside tables or in the game room. Good place to get away from it all and spend time with family.</text>

<text>A wonderful place to stay while visiting Sequoia National Park and seeing the Trees, doings some hikes, and visiting Kings canyon. My wife and I stayed here for 3-4 nights and I will not complain. We came May 7th, 2019 - May 10th, 2019

This place has the antique feel of an original lodge built in the mountains and is ran professionally.

The staff is friendly, the beds are comfortable from the sheets and pillows down to the softness/hardness of the mattress was to our liking. We felt like a king and queen sleeping on it and had good nights sleep every night. You may want earplugs when you sleep as people can be heard in the hallways if they're walking by and talking or closing doors somewhat loudly.

We didn't eat lunch there but had the all you can eat breakfast every morning and had dinner there 3 nights in a row.

The breakfast is decent for the price and the dinner is high quality but you will pay the price for it. Servers were excellent and friendly.
Breakfast is around $15-$20 per person and dinner is around $35-$50 if you are drinking alcohol.

They have a gift shop with everything you may need in case you forget something like snacks or chap stick etc.

Their dining room is open and makes you feel grand.

It's a good place that you should stay at if you want to remember yourself having a great time. Visit this place if you can or skip the hotel and just check out the trees.<//text><pictures>None<//pictures>< resp>

<Time>1559845957621</Time><Rating>1<//Rating>< text>
I had high hopes of what our time would be at the Wuksachi lodge. It was an experience that we splurged on and thought that it would enhance our enjoyment of Sequoia National Park. It was actually quite the opposite. The room was over 80 degrees when we arrived. The maintenance man came out after two calls about it. He turned off the wall units, but this still did not cool our "Superior" room below 75¬∫ F even with the windows open. I have never seen a baby pack-n-play as cheap as the one that was given for my daughter to sleep in. You could literally feel the bars through the mattress in it.

The Peak restaurant was the single largest disappointment. It is everything you would expect from a vendor that has a monopoly. The food was of terrible quality for the prices. The burger I ordered the first night was not cooked to temperature. The restaurant was out of milk at breakfast the first morning, meaning we could not give my one year old daughter milk. The kid's spaghetti that my kids ordered the second night made them both sick. The last morning we were there, they were literally running out of everything to the point where you had to ask the wait staff for each item. The only server that was helpful was Trevor.

I would not recommend the Wuksachi Lodge or the Peak Restaurant to anyone. You would be better off staying and eating outside of the park.

The Lodge sent me a survey after our trip which I gave them the same feedback as posted above and asked to be contacted. 6 weeks have passed and I still have not received a call.< /text>

<rating>5</rating><Text>The Wuksachi Lodge had a delicious restaurant inside, a small gift shop, and a comfortable seating area. The rooms are a short drive away, and boy are they pretty. The beds are comfy, the bathroom is clean, and you don't feel like you're on top of each other. But the views are really what elevate these rooms. I can't imagine there is a room in that lodge with a bad view. We were surrounded by trees, and you just felt so in touch with the park, despite being in a very comfortable bed. The breakfast was a buffet, and while it wasn't cheep, it was delicious! I ate so much it was crazy. I could write a whole separate post on the parks themselves. They are some of my favorite places in the world. So many different features all in one place, it's incredible. Plus the lodge offers a free shuttle all through these wonderful works of nature. This is a wonderful experience. You must must MUST book your room well in advance, sometimes a year out. <date>1531094400000<//date>< rating>
None</rating>
<review>You couldnt ask for a better location in Sequoia than Wuksachi Lodge. Located 2 miles from Lodgepole (which is where they have a marketplace, grill, and the shuttle for the other Sequoia attractions), Wuksachi is right where you want to be located in the park. The lodge itself and the room was clean, but unfortunately when we were there in July 2018, they were under construction on the grounds, both in front of the lodge and next to the dining room. This really takes away from the experience, and I was surprised they were doing the work during peak season? The lodge itself has very little when it comes to amenities. There is a restaurant on site that actually had great food at a mid-level price. The downside is you need to book reservations for dinner, so unless you get them in early, you will find yourself eating at either 5:00 or 8:00. There is not much else to do at the lodge. No pool or game room or anything like that. That may not be an issue for most since the main reason to visit Sequoia is to be in the park, but for people who like to break up their adventures with a day at the resort, there is nothing to do at this one. They did have a nice stargazing retreat at night which was provided free of cost, and that was a lot of fun. In terms of the rooms, be aware that they do not have A/C, just window and ceiling fans. Since it was Summer when we were at the lodge, it was pretty warm during the day and the room was stuffy. Thankfully it cooled down enough at night.</review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Response>
None</Response>

<rating>4<//rating><text>We stayed one night. The main Lodge is nice, with a warm fire and nice restaurant. It's fairly new and is very "mountain lodge" in decor - rustic and comfortable. The actual rooms are in three separate buildings. The location of the rooms could be a problem for people with disabilities ( not a problem for us) but if I had trouble with a lot of walking and some uphill walkways, it wouldn't be good. The rooms were clean, no wifi in rooms, but you could get it in the main Lodge building. The location is in one of the most beautiful places on the earth, so that is biggest plus, in my opinion. Meals were not included, so consider that when booking. The only place to eat ( breakfast, lunch or dinner) is at the restaurant in main Lodge building. Full breakfast was around $14, continental was $8. We had dinner in restaurant. The food was very good at average-high price. It has to be trucked in over hairy mountain roads, so I'm sure that is reason for prices.</text>< pictures>

<text>I give Wuksachi Lodge a 5 star because of the amazing service and kindness of the workers.

--So I brought my brand new Canon Rebel t5i to take photos and videos on in Sequoia National Park because it is spectacularly beautiful! But, this was a very brand new Camera, like I got it only a week ago and I bought it from my uncle and he gave me some other cool gear with it too, including a charger. Unfortunately, it was the wrong charger for my camera. So toward the end of the first day our of three day trip, I was devastated because my camera was on low battery and I was going to not be able to film and photograph the rest of the trip. HOWEVER, I asked the workers at the front desk if any of them had a spare charger and they thought of all their coworkers who had cameras. Eventually, one of the coworkers had the exact same camera and the right charger and she let me use hers. Her name was Victoria Dunbar and she even insisted on letting me bring HER charger back to my room to charge my camera for the duration of my stay!

The views from where we stayed are also incredible and the bedroom was very big and spacious. The cots they have are also the best cots I have ever slept on!

<user_name>Mike Simpson</user_name><Time>1512453447631</Time><Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
Had a wonderful time staying at the Wuksachi Lodge. The location is excellent, only a couple of miles away from the best attractions of the Sequoia National Park. We visited the peak restaurant for 2 dinners and breakfast. Other than the steak knives being dull, the food was great and their drinks were refreshing. They had good prices and selection for being such an isolated restaurant. We also ordered the box lunches since we were going hiking all day, and they were very satisfying. The lodge is where you check in and the location of the restaurant and gift shop, and the rooms are in their own separate buildings detached from the lodge. There is a path that travels between the two that is about a 5 minute walk.</text>

Casey DuPont</user_name>
<Time>1539408731918</Time><Rate>4<//Rate>< Review>
Wuksachi is located at the top of Sequoia NP, close to the sequoia groves an King's Canyon NP. It is a unique setup, the main common area of front desk and restaurant is separate (a short 5 minute walk) from all the rooms. The restaurant, gift shop, heated deck, and front desk have a mountain Lodge setting and mountain view. The room accommodation portion of Wuksachi is more of a very basic hotel. The room provides basic beds, a small fridge, small TV, and and attached bathroom. While it meets all needs, I believe the rooms were overpriced and the room buildings require some renovations. Do not expect anything like a Lodge.<//Review>

<review>We went up for a few days and had a nice stay in the snow. The hotel was well staffed although they all insist on calling you Mr and Mrs, which I found a bit too formal for my liking. The restaurant had quite a selection for being in such a remote area and the bartender was fun to talk to. The drinks they made really fit the weather. Speaking of which, if you intend to go up during snow season, be sure you buy snow chains and learn how to put them on BEFORE you make the drive. Many people got into minor accidents or had no idea how to put on chains when they needed to. Lucky many of the people there will help you out, if you don't run into anyone and you can't put on your chains, you might be stuck for several hours like some of the folks I met.< /review>< UserId.>

Wuksachi Lodge will over book!  How do I know, we booked, gave the credit card, got the confirmation and started on the way up the hill. This was a direct reservation no 3rd party was used. When we talked with them they stated they don't use any 3rd party sites.  Note this place is in the park so you must pay a fee to get to it. What made me more fired up was the screen I could see they had over booked people the next two days, too. They had no place for us to go except to spend an hour and half going back down to three rivers out of the park.  Book at your own risk! It's my understanding this is owned by the Delaware North Company (DNC) who also has the market next door while trying to find if a camping option could work. One star is as low as it will let me go but it should have no stars. If you had the same issue please let people know, it's a long way to go without another option. #WillOverBook #Hotel #WuksachiLodge</Text>

<Review>I'm writing this primarily to tie-up a many-month feedback lapse: One of the lodge employees, with a name-tag denoting Josil, very kindly provided my wife and I a set of lengthy explanations to a long list of inquiries. A lot of detail garnered from her personal experiences helped us significantly. This was while we were staying at the lodge where where she worked as a receptionist, not the restaurant-portion.

However, in coming here I've seen a perplexing mix of restaurant reviews. There must be some variability in chefs! To provide our tip on that balance - the restaurant was fantastic. The portions were large - much larger than expected! Very pleasing when you've been traipsing about the Sequoias all day. (Also worth noting - they provided gluten-free options, a must for my wife.)  The workload on the wait-staff was quite high, but provided great service despite this. Equally important, the ambiance of the place was lovely and perfectly suited the external environs/views thereof. < review>
A charming lodge in the beautiful Sequoia NP. Beds were a bit on the firm side and could use more pillows. Staff was friendly and helpful in navigating us to areas of the park. Nothing beats stepping out of your hotel room to a gorgeous mountain view.

Some things to note:
- The path from the check in area to the three lodges isn't particularly well lit. Make sure to bring a flashlight when walking about at night.
- When you access the Sequoia set of rooms, there are a set of shallow, uneven stairs with no handrail. However, there is a ramp which makes for a much smoother walk.
- The front desk fails to mention this, but it is on the check in materials that a bellhop can bring your luggage to your room. You can also get a luggage cart in your lodge "house" and wheel it down to the car.
- There is no pool. Believe it or not, someone asked the bartender if there was a pool. No, but there are streams and lakes.
- Be prepared to disconnect from your cellphone. Wifi is often spotty and cellular service is practically nonexistent.

Meals are not included with the room rate. The buffet breakfast that is in the restaurant adjoining the check-in area of the lodge is average and I don't feel it is worth the $16-20 unless you eat more than one plate of food. (The prices for the buffet vary based on whether you get the cold or hot breakfast, and the price seems to vary based on whether it is the week or weekend, and the time of year you visit.) It is a typical "American" breakfast of potatoes, bacon, sausage, scrambled eggs, pancakes, pastries, toast, bagels, cereal, some fruit, and oatmeal. There isn't anything special about the breakfast. The pizza from the restaurant, however, is delicious. So are most of the dishes served for lunch and dinner.<//review>

< Text>
The service at the restaurant is slow and disorganized. Be prepared to wait an hour even for a simple sandwich! However, the atmosphere is amazing, with gorgeous views of the mountains, so the wait can be bearable with good company, an appetizer and some drinks.

The food is fresh and relatively healthy for a restaurant, with vegan and vegetarian options available. While the food isn't amazing on its own, for the elevation at 2000m+ (7000ft+) above sea level, the quality is amazing.<//Text>

We came in early April and the place was still mostly snowed in. The lodge and the rooms are a couple of hundred meters apart. The rooms themselves are the standard hotel fair, but take heed that there are no elevators, so if you are on the second or third floor you will have to carry your luggage (if you have any) up the long walkway from the car parking to the building and then up the stairs.
In the end, the place is amazing since it is in an amazing place.< /review>

I've been to the lodge several times in the past and the food has always been excellent. This time, however, my wife and I were unable to eat as the restaurant closes from 230-430. I was upset because we arrived at 225 and the hostess would not seat us and seemed annoyed that we even asked. I normally love the lodge's food and that's why I gave it a 4, but the service just wasn't there this time. Still a great place to visit and eat at though!</text>

<Review>We stayed here for one night on the weekend in mid December. The Superior room was large and clean. If you bring children, definitely book this room. The atmosphere was spectacular! <user_name>Emilia Batchiyski<//user_name><time>1495695801699<//time>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< review>
Whenever go to Sequoia National Park I always stop at Wuksachi Lodge for a meal at the restaurant. It is conveniently located just off the main road and just couple of miles from Lodgepole. The food choices and atmosphere are as in a class restaurant, not as the usual fast food choices usually found at remote locations like this. Highly recommend for a quality meal or a romantic dinner by the fireplace.<//review>

<review>Arrived on Sunday before Labor Day with my family of 7 expecting no rooms available. To my surprise, they had a standard room and a suite. They were kind to show me both rooms to see which suits better. I ended choosing the suite and they even gave me a break on the price.

<Rate>4</Rate>< review>
What an experience to stay in a National Park. Accommodations are adequate. Price is amazing, we even got a Groupon which gave us free breakfast for 2 for two days. Although the breakfast buffet leaves much to be desired, it was free. Dinner was a bit pricey and the two seafood options (shrimp tacos and rainbow trout) we chose were not worth it. Overall we would stay here again.< /review>

< text>
I loved this place it's like you don't want to go back to reality.  Loved the quietness and their service. Employees at check in and at the lodge were helpful and friendly. They even provide you with toiletries (toothbrush and tooth paste)need to ask though.  The rooms have shampoo and body wash pumps  inside the shower.There is only one place too eat and dinner is expensive but what makes it much more pricey is that you Have Too Pay your waiter a tip and your tab tells you how much YOU HAVE TO PAY that's the only negative thing I can say about this lodge. I believe they should make it into a buffet and that way more people would go up there.  The stay is expensive as it is and you can't drive no where because the road that gets you too the top 8,500 feet has sharp turns and it's dangerous to be driving at night.  By the way the room has no microwave. I went during thanksgiving week 2016. yes we got snow the next day.< /text>

Overall I enjoyed my stay. I knew there was snow but i wasnt prepared for 90 inch of it. They did have paths cleared out dso that was good. It got a bit confusing when driving up though. The only reason i gave 4 stars is because there was a good walk from the room to the service desk/restaurant. Also the dinner at the restaurant was pricey and not very good. The breakfast was better. It was basically the only place to eat while out there except going down a ways from the lodge to the store where you can buy packaged sandwiches and microwave food ect. Fyi no microwave in the room just a mini fridge and a coffee pot. I will stay here again but be more prepared with the food part lol.</Review>

<response>None< /response><UserId.>111428638507422761457</UserId.><Date>1345654710439<//Date>< Review>
I'm writing this review only on the restaurant, at which my wife and I ate twice during our vacation in Sequoia National Park.

The food was pricey, as I would expect from any restaurant in such a unique location, but I didn't feel it was bad quality. My wife and I both enjoyed what we ordered. I ordered the turkey burger both days, and my wife ordered the prime rib sandwich. I will say that it wasn't any more expensive than the Grant's Grove restaurant, however. If you want to eat "real" food (by that I mean, not junk food) in the Sequoia park, these are your only two options.

I can corroborate a previous statement that we were told dinners were by reservation only; however, we went back to the lodge later to use the facilities, and I asked if they had any dinner openings, and I was told enthusiastically that they did, and from what I could tell, the dinning room was veritably empty.< /Review>

<text>Picture-window vistas of the sequoias and a muted Indian theme in the decor, with an unexpected Japanese touch in the interesting earthenware dishes. Menu has that depressingly burger-centric mix familiar from American ski resorts. A Martian would come away innocent of the knowledge that this restaurant is perched above the preeminent fruit-and-vegetable-growing region of North America, such is the generic, corporate feel of the menu.

Service on my visit was slipshod, with a fifteen-minute wait to order. A competent salmon sandwich arrived with fries which a charitable soul would describe as lukewarm.

A prime location suffering from the slackness bred of monopoly, I suspect.< /text><pics>None</pics><response>None< /response>< Gmap_id>

< Text>
Check-in personnel need to know and share more info about shuttle service. We learned more by overhearing another's conversation. The staff was never rude or mean just not as knowledgeable as we expected. Clean room, hot water was extremely hot and was at times too hot. The room had a fridge but no microwave. The fridge's thermostat was buried under the 'freezer' section's ice and as such it never got the fridge section nicely cold because it always thought it was cold enough. We appreciated the shuttle service but two drvers we had were very curt while another driver was very friendly and helpful. Most shuttle rides were very crowded and we would've done more driving if parking was more generous. The lodge restaurant had, at best, reasonable food but was overpriced and not worth the cost. Given another chance we would buy our food from the lodgepole market (2 miles away) and prepare sandwiches ourselves. Example: day one we bought an $8 burger (from the children's menu) that was worth $16, but on day two we paid $18 for a bison burger which we never want to eat again. The fresh fruit, available at every meal we ate, was always very good but repetitive (pineapple, cantelope, and honeydew). The meal portions we're good. The four stars were mainly due to location and condition of the hotel. It was in a beautiful place and hard to not appreciate the view. Being located within the park saved us an hour plus (minimum) drive each day to reach the sights. We would recommend the lodge and, if we go back, we will stay there again.< /Text>

<Review>I really feel this place does a much better job than what I received. There were a lot of headaches in the beginning, but management straightened everything out. The room was clean, the dinner staff was exceptionally friendly and easy-going, and one can not complain about the easy access to the national and state parks. Had it not been for Mr. J, I would have left a 1-star review and a much longer description.

A few side-notes: Dinner is a bit over-priced, they should have wild-caught fish at those price points. I had a couple whiskey-doubles (Glenlivet & Chivas) which put me back 45 bucks, felt like I was at a freaking night-club in San Fran.

Make sure you know whether or not the roads are open via the route you plan to take in. They may close the northern route because of snow and it will suck to have to go ALL the way around (+4 hours minimum).

The team knows the wifi situation is no good. That being said, after speaking with management, the fix they were in the final stages of implementing should solve a lot of problems, looks like I just came on the wrong day. Ignore bad WIFI comments before today's date. If bad WIFI comments persist after March 15 or so, I'd say their solution was no good and they have to continue working on it.

Hope this helps someone!< /Review>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>

<time>1519253386025<//time>< Rating>
1</Rating>
<Review>Due to the many highly rated reviews, I was expecting more than what I paid for. $230 as a discounted AAA rate isn't peanuts, and for that price I was expecting a resort and not a motel.

First, there is no parking directly in front of the reception for guest to quickly check in. You would still have to park in the parking lot and run to the lobby to check in. I guess I didn't look as good as the previous guest, because I didn't get my room upgraded. Hotel staff greeted me and gave me some brief information to get my stay started.

Upon getting to the rooms, I had to park in a no parking zone to get my bags out. Though there were many luggage carts, there were no attendants to help unload and transport to the room. Baggage was then lugged to the second story up the stairs due to the lack of elevator.

The room was about the same size as an average yet dated Hampton inn with far less amenities. No microwave, no DVD player, different colored bulbs (maybe it's just a pet peeve of mine), each bed had only two small and flat pillows each, linen was pretty rough, and the comforter had stains on them. Corners, curtains, and ceiling fan were dusty and had cob webs. Tub was cracked, tub spout would not operate properly when attempting to switch to the shower head and the shower head was weak and seemed to not operate properly as well. Shower had a soap dispenser, yet you had your choice of lime scented shampoo or lime scented shampoo. The toilet flushed like it was made by NASA and required 300 psi to propel your flush into space (sorry I'll leave the jokes out) it was loud.

The walls are pretty thin and the hotel allows pets. The WiFi is only mediocre in the lobby and pretty much non existent in the rooms. Vending machine was down and there were no other community amenities near the rooms.

For the price I'd expect at least a continental breakfast and due to the lack of activities available at the lodge, there could have been complimentary sack lunches as well (Hampton inn does this free of charge).

I guess I was expecting a camp lodge experience with campfires going to enjoy, s'mores,  and a friendly old bearded guy playing campfire songs for the guests. After all, the experience of seeing the Sequoia are a once in a lifetime experience, and I was hoping the lodging would be as well.

Lastly, if you book online you will be charged a deposit (equivalent to a one night stay), when you check out, the entire bill will be charged to your card. If you used a credit card the deposit will be credited back to your account in a couple days, if debit, 7-30 days depending on your bank.

It is apparent that businesses in these rare locations do not place customer service high on their agenda. Where else would you stay and eat so close to the Sequoia? And I guess this is why they don't have to strive so hard as other competitors.

I'm new at this review thing, though it is well overdue, customer service in this country is not what it used to be. I am not one of those guys that gives jiffy lube coffee a five star rating, and neither should the reviewers (no offense to jiffy lube coffee).

To prove my point, at the end of my stay I was greeted with my bill at the lobby and was not asked how my stay was. Not one to split hairs, but it would have been nice to be asked. Sorry wuksachi lodge, it wasn't worth the visit.

Thank you owner for acknowledging my experience, I post not only to help your business grow but to allow business owners the ability to improve and keep an edge on the corporate conglomerates that corner each market. In any business, customer experience and service should be the corner Stone to any business. Without the customer, there would be no business. The location of your lodge is in a beautiful area and I wish the best of business for you in the future! Regards JV<//Review>< Pics>
None< /Pics>

I will pass along this review to the appropriate managers for their discussion and usefulness in reminding our front desk to ask each and every guest, how their stay was. I again apologize and hope that you reached your next destination safely.'}<//Resp>< GmapID>

<Review>There is no A/C. At night it gets cool enough that this isn't a major problem, but I still wished for it once or twice. You will have no cell coverage at all - phone, texting, data - nothing. That's true in pretty much the whole park, so nothing against the hotel, but be aware that their wifi is abysmal, so while, yes, you CAN get SOME things online, be sure to have downloaded all your maps, audio books, guides, and whatever else you were planning on using while you were here BEFORE you come. Again, the hotel probably can't get anything better, so this is more of a warning than a complaint. TIP: if you are coming as a group, consider getting long-range walkie talkies or something like that.

The water comes out of the tap at a VERY slow rate - 28.8 ml / second or .46 gallons / minute. I understand the need to conserve water, but it shouldn't take a full minute to fill up 2 water bottles.

My door didn't close all the way unless you pulled on it, which in and of itself wasn't a big deal, but lent to the general feeling that this building is older and could use a bit of a freshening up, although I acknowledge that some may find it more of a charming, quaint sort of feel and prefer it that way.

As far as I could tell, the only difference bergen the standard and deluxe rooms was that the more expensive ones are ever so slightly bigger and have a chair. Big woop - I recommend the cheaper room unless you have a need for a few extra square feet of space.

You must walk a short distance from the car to your room. Some may like the feeling of remoteness that this gives, but it isn't particularly handicap-friendly, if that's an issue for you.

The beds were comfortable, the rooms were clean, and the location was fantastic. Really, when you get right down to it, that's all that really matters, right?<//Review>< GmapID>

<review>I stayed here because of its proximity to the Giant Forest at Sequoia.  There are actually no giant sequoias that I saw in the lodge area--you need to drive a few minutes down the road.  The room I stayed in was nice.  It had no air conditioning--just a window fan--but a/c wasn't needed during my stay in early August, as daytime highs were only in the low 70's.  WiFi was extremely slow, but free.  There's no cell phone signal here as of the time of this review, so you really need the WiFi if you feel the need to be connected to the outside world.  The lodge's restaurant--The Pines--was adequate (not fantastic), and the bottled beers quite expensive.  The all-you-can eat barbecue dinner at nearby Wolverton was a nice change.  Overall, a perfectly enjoyable stay.< /review><Time>1376089549319<//Time><rating>3</rating><Gmap_id>0x80955e7bbfa947a1:0x569f3289d86ec019<//Gmap_id>< user>

2</rating>
<review>This not Giant Forest Lodge.
It is a place to stay in Sequoia.
I found that I could rent a small RV for what they charge to stay here. Next time I will rent the RV and stay at Lodge pole. WL is pleasent enough, but the design of separate lodging buildings from lobby and reasturant make it feel like no architect was used. You cannot drive up to the front door to check in. The long paths to the lodging buildings are poorly maintained. Be prepared to lug your bags up and down stairs. Rooms could have had balconies to enjoy the lodge pole forest but the design doesn't understand that we are here to be involved with nature. The real shocker was the notice that the water does not meet California standards. Breakfast buffett was executed poorly. The food was often cold and dishes not available to serve ones self. Tables and chairs were crammed in so guests often were bumping into seated dinners.
The wifi worked well in my room, but that's not why I am here.
The beds are soft and they have no backboards.
Got rained out of Ranger talk at lodge pole and came back to dine early.  Even though there were open tables I was told I had to wait. When seated, got bread with oil but no vinigar.  Getting hot water refills while waiting for dinner was difficult.  It took 50 minutes for food to arrive.  My wife got plain dried out and cold rice instead of what was ordered.  The whole operation with armature and inefficient.  Definatly a disappointment at high prices
Update: Delaware North is wants big money for names in National Parks. The Parks and the names are our patrimony.</review>< Pics>

We experienced the rudest check-in in almost 40 years of travelling around the world. The lady at the front desk told us in an arrogant and smug tone that the phones are not working, the internet will be slow due to a satellite link and that we have to remove all food from the car.
